                        MICROCELL SYSTEM OVERVIEW

Microcell layout is a symbolic layout system. The microcell idea takes the
traditional cells a new step "down":

   Cell: an area layout (probably rectangular) which contains an arbitrary
   custom layout and edge connectors.

   Macrocell: Logically, a cell that consists of a collection of subcells
   with interconnect. May refer to any unitized complex function.

   Microcell: A cell containing one or a small number of features present
   on an IC, such as a contact, via, etc.

The microcell contruction starts with a layout grid. The size of the grid
is determined so that each feature we need to represent can be present
in a grid cell, adjacent to any other cell, without possible design rule
violation. That is:

                 -------------
                 | A | B | C |
                 -------------
                 | D | E | F |
                 -------------
                 | G | H | I |
                 -------------

If cell E can have any of A, B, C, D, F, G, H, and I be any given cell
in any possible combination without design rule violation, the system is
valid.
The basis of the system is a "book" of microcells. At present there are
only two books:

   1. Single layer metal.

   2. Double layer metal.

Actually the second is simply the addition of a set of cells to the first.
it should be obvious from the above that the system is rule free, or correct
by construct. This leaves only a set of "construction rules" that dictate how
the cell is built.
The object of the microcell generator is to build a standard cell. All such
cells MUST be rectangular. The microcell generator can also generate
macrocells, which also must be rectangular. Typically, an IC build will
include the following steps:

   1. Construct cells. Each leaf cell is constructed into a cell.

   2. Construct macrocells. Each cell containing other cells is
   built by placement of defined cells and then routing between them.
   This process terminates with the macrocell that defines the IC
   function.

   3. Construct pad cells. Typically each pad cell needed is manually
   generated.

   4. Construct pad macrocells. Since cells must be rectangular, these
   will consist of side cells, and perhaps corner spacers. Alternately,
   a clockwise or counter-clockwise overlap can be used to enable access
   to the corners.
   A pseudo-pad ring can also be constructed for IC's that will serve
   as both standalone IC's and macrocells.
